Date: PUBLISHED: February 10, 2019 at 12:57 pm | UPDATED: February 12, 2019 at 3:26 pm
Caption: BART will limit its service hours beginning Monday to allow workers more time to complete a $267 million seismic retrofit of the Transbay Tube, along with other repairs and upgrades throughout the system. (File photo by Karl Mondon/Contra Costa Times)
Credit/Source: (File photo by Karl Mondon/Contra Costa Times)

Caption: San Francisco, CA November 1967 – Binocular-shaped sections of the transbay tube were constructed in a shipyard then sunk in the Bay. The tube withstood the Loma Prieta earthquake of 1989, running 24-hour service just 12 hours after the quake struck. But, agency officials want to make sure it’s still safe should the center of a catastrophic earthquake strike closer to the core of the system. (Fran Ortiz / Oakland Tribune)
BART plans to take advantage of the extra work time to complete other repairs and upgrades of the system. (Graphic courtesy BART)
BART’s Sunday service will be limited. (Graphic courtesy BART)
The Early Bird Bus service will serve 21 BART stations with destinations in the East Bay, Peninsula, and San Francisco. (Graphic courtesy BART)
Locations where trains will start service beginning Feb. 11. (Graphic courtesy BART)

Joe Raedle/Getty Images
						MIAMI, FL – DECEMBER 22:  A copy of a IRS 1040 tax form is seen at an H&R Block office on the day President Donald Trump signed the Republican tax cut bill in Washington, DC  on December 22, 2017 in Miami, Florida. Kathy Pickering, vice president of regulatory affairs and executive director of The Tax Institute at H&R Block released a statement about the new tax bill saying, ” It’s going to change the way you think about and plan your income taxes. You’ll need to take a fresh look at your individual situation to know your outcome and new strategies to use to get the best tax outcome.”  (Photo by Joe Raedle/Getty Images)
Are high-earners fleeing the high-tax Empire State of New York because of the Trump tax overhaul? New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo thinks so. (Getty Images)

California officials aren’t concerned — yet — about the drop in tax receipts in December and January and instead believe high-income residents are just delaying their tax payments because of the lower deductions for state and local taxes in the federal tax reform law is giving them less incentive to pay early. (Ray Chavez/Bay Area News Group)

Former California Gov. Jerry Brown famously built up the state’s Rainy Day fund in his two terms after inheriting a $27 billion deficit in 2011. (Katy Murphy/Bay Area News Group) (Katy Murphy/Bay Area News Group)

Caption: Family and friends of Agustin “Augie” Gonsalez, who was shot and killed by Hayward police in November, hold a vigil in his memory and to demonstrate that they believe the shooting was not justified in front of Hayward City Hall in Hayward, Calif., on Friday, Jan. 4, 2019. The 29-year-old father of two, of Lathrop, was visiting his former girlfriend on O’Neil Avenue when a witness reported he was brandishing a knife and acting erratically, according to police. Two officers who responded fired a total of 13 shots, hitting him multiple times, police said. Gonsalez was carrying a razor blade rather than a knife as was initially reported in the 911 call, police said.  (Anda Chu/Bay Area News Group)

Caption: With her arms and legs shackled, Marjorie Knoller (center) is escorted with a group of prisoners to the Tehama County Superior Court House before her arraignment hearing on Wednesday, March 28, 2001 in Red Bluff, Calif. Knoller and her husband Robert Noel were arrested yesterday after a grand jury issued a warrant for their arrest. Two dogs owned by Knoller and Noel mauled and killed their neighbor Diane Whipple in the hallway of their apartment in San Francisco in early January. (Jose Carlos Fajardo/Bay Area News Group archive)
Credit/Source: (Jose Carlos Fajardo/Bay Area News Group archive)

Caption: Diane Whipple, 33, who was fatally mauled Jan. 26, 2001, outside her San Francisco apartment by at least one of two huge Presa Canario dogs, is shown in this undated file photo. (Jose Carlos Fajardo/Bay Area News Group archive)
Credit/Source: (Jose Carlos Fajardo/Bay Area News Group archive)

Caption: Marjorie Knoller reacts to her sentencing inside the Superior Court in San Francisco, Calif., Monday July 15, 2002. Knoller was sentenced to four years in prison for involuntary manslaughter. Diane Wipple, Knoller's neighbor, was mauled to death by Knoller's dog a year earlier.  (Bob Larson/Bay Area News Group archive)

Penny Whipple, the mother of 33-year-old Diane Whipple, leaves San Francisco Superior Court Tuesday April 10, 2001 after filing a wrongful death lawsuit with her attorney Ronald Rouda. Diane Whipple, a St. Mary's College lacrosse coach, was killed in a January dog mauling at her San Francisco apartment. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group archive)

Bane, an English mastiff-Canary Island dog mix, shown in this undated file photo, is one of two dogs that fatally mauled 33-year-old Diane Whipple in front of her apartment on Jan. 26, 2001. Dog owner Marjorie Knoller, 46, who was present during the attack, is charged with second-degree murder, involuntary manslaughter and having a mischievous animal that killed a human being. Her husband, Robert Noel, 60, faces the latter two charges. Both dogs have been put-down since the attack. (Robert Noel via Bay Area News Group)
Credit/Source: (Robert Noel via Bay Area News Group)

Caption: Robert Noel is shown with one of his mastiff-Canary Island mix dogs in this undated file photo. Noel and his wife, Marjorie Knoller, are the owners of two dogs involved in the fatal mauling of a college lacrosse coach, Diane Whipple, who died Friday, Jan. 26, 2001. (Courtesy of Robert Noel via Bay Area News Group)
Credit/Source: (Courtesy of Robert Noel via Bay Area News Group)

Caption: District Attorney Terence Hallinan, center, flanked by assistant district attorney Jim Hammer, right, and assistant district attorney Kimberly Guilfoyle Newsom, comments Wednesday, March 20, 2002 after the jury informed the judge they had reached verdicts on four of five counts in the Diane Whipple dog mauling case at the Los Angeles County Courthouse in Los Angeles. Robert Noel and his wife, Marjorie Knoller, are charged in the death of their neighbor Whipple, 33, who was fatally mauled on Jan. 26,2001, outside her apartment by at least one of the couple's dogs. (Dan Honda/Bay Area News Group archive)

Nedra Ruiz (cq), attorney for Marjorie Knoller, lets her feelings known, during a press briefing at the Los Angeles County Courthouse, in Los Angeles, Calif., as the jury was given the case in the Diane Whipple dog mauling trial on Tuesday, March 19, 2002. The highly publicized trial is now in the hands of the jury and the waiting begins. (Dan Honda/Bay Area News Group archive)

Sharon Smith (dark hair facing camera), partner of dog mauling victim Diane Whipple, was comforted by members of the St. Mary's lacrosse team April 13, 2001 after an arraignment hearing for the defendants Robert Noel and Marjorie Knoller. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group archive)

With a somber face, Marjorie Knoller closes her eyes as she listens to Superior Court Judge John Garaventa during her arraignment hearing at the Tehama County Superior Court House on Wednesday, March 28, 2001 in Red Bluff, Calif. Knoller and her husband Robert Noel were arrested yesterday after a grand jury issued a warrant for their arrest. (Jose Carlos Fajardo/Bay Area News Group archive)
Credit/Source: (Jose Carlos Fajardo/Bay Area News Group archive)

Date: February 8, 2019 at 11:43 am
Caption: Delaney Van Riper opens a bag of cheese with a pair of scissors on Wednesday, May 9, 2018, in Santa Cruz, Calif. Van Riper, a UC Santa Cruz student, has a degenerative muscle condition called Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease. The conditions makes task such opening bottles or bags of food difficult since she does not have full strength in her hands. Van Riper hopes through the use of the gene-editing technology called CRISPR, she can overcome her condition. (Randy Vazquez/ Bay Area News Group)

Caption: A leucistic bald eagle, photographed on the Coyote Creek Trail in San Jose earlier this month. The condition is very rare in raptors, occurring in about one per 1,800 birds.
The bald eagle has a snowy appearance, but it's the result of leucism, a genetic flaw that steals the color from some feathers.
Birds with leucism have shorter life spans, partly because the lack of melanin -- coloring -- weakens the feathers, which can make flying more difficult.
Is this an albino finch, or a leucistic finch? The orange legs and black eyes indicate it's lleucistic, meaning it has a defect in its pigment cells, which robbed it of color.

A rare white sparrow visits a Rio Vista backyard. The white is not caused by albinism, but by a different type of mutation of pigment. In this case, the bird's feathers are white, but the eyes, beak and legs maintain their normal coloring.

Caption:
US Senator from California, Kamala Harris, addresses the media January, 21 2019 at Howard University in Washington, DC after announcing earlier in the day that she is seeking to become the first African American woman to hold the office of US president, joining an already-crowded field of Democrats lining up to take on Donald Trump. – Harris joins Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts, Hawaii congresswoman Tulsi Gabbard, New York Senator Kirsten Gillibrand and former housing secretary Julian Castro, among others, either in the race or exploring a run for the 2020 Democratic nomination. Nearly 22 months before the 2020 election, the battle for the White House is already firming up, as Americans begin to assess who might be the opposition party nominee to challenge Trump for control of the White House.

Harris made the announcement on the national holiday honoring civil rights movement icon Martin Luther King Jr., whom she said her mother met. (Photo by EVA HAMBACH / AFP)EVA HAMBACH/AFP/Getty Images

Date: PUBLISHED: February 6, 2019 at 2:48 pm | UPDATED: February 7, 2019 at 9:41 am
Caption: Joshua Pawlik who was shot and killed by four Oakland Police officers on March 11, 2018. (Pawlik family)

Oakland civil rights attorney, John Burris, right, sits next to fellow attorney Adanté Pointer, as Burris talks to the media  announcing the filing of a federal civil rights lawsuit in San Francisco on behalf of Kelly Pawlik, the mother of Joshua Pawlik who was shot and killed by four officers of the Oakland police department during a press conference in Oakland, Calif., on Wednesday, Feb. 6, 2019. The incident, that occurred on March 11, 2018, The complaint alleges that the police officers confronted an unconscious Mr. Pawlik who way lying between two residential houses in North Oakland. After unsuccessfully awakening him by shouting and loudspeakers for over 45 minutes, the officers deployed an armed military vehicle. The officers waited for Pawlik to awake, and when he moved his upper torso and began looking around, still seeming semi-conscious, the police officer shot Pawlik. (Doug Duran/Bay Area News Group)

Napa Valley Wine Train Valentine’s Day specials are available Feb. 14-17 in
Napa. Choose from a variety of lunch and dinner experiences, from an
evening under the stars being serenaded by a strolling musician, to a day
exploring wineries followed by a multiple course meal

A Victorian Valentine Ball will be held on Feb. 9 at The Haas-Lilienthal
House in San Francisco. The Valentine-themed fundraiser will have an
emphasis on the late 19th century. Learn to dance the waltz and polka and
play Victorian trivia games.

Valentine’s Burlesque Show Featuring Carmel Delights will be held at 8 p.m.
Feb. 14-16, Paper Wing theatre in Monterey. Romance, comedy and sexiness.

Enjoy Kid Koala: Nufonia Must Fall, Feb. 13-14 at Hammer Theatre Center in
San Jose. A tale of a robot who falls in love with a roboticist is
performed live using a team of puppeteers, miniature sets and film editors,
all live-scored by a string quartet and DJ.

Valentine's Day at Peña Pachamama! will be performed on Feb. 14 in San
Francisco. Join Eddy Navia and the Pachamama band, with a line up of Latin
and Cuban musicians and special guest Carolina Lugo's and  Carolé Acuña's
Ballet Flamenco.

The 26-year old rapper — whose real name is Sha Yaa Bin Abraham Joseph — was arrested in the southern city of Atlanta Sunday by immigration agents who say he is in fact a British citizen. Date: PUBLISHED: February 4, 2019 at 7:28 am | UPDATED: February 7, 2019 at 1:05 pm
Caption: Kate Spencer, of Fast Raft Ocean Safaris, on her boat in Monterey last month. (Randy Vazquez – Bay Area News Group)

Two adult humpback whales have a conversation with body language as they roll onto their right sides and loudly slap their left flippers against the water on Oct. 3, 2018 in Monterey Bay. These two might have a lot to talk about: One of them (CRC-10727) was first photographed as an adult in 1998, so it may be well over 30 years old. The other, Bottlenose (CRC-10846), is a female who is over 20 and had a calf in 2017. (Courtesy of Kate Spencer, Fast Raft Ocean Safaris)
Credit/Source: (Courtesy of Kate Spencer, Fast Raft Ocean Safaris)

Caption: A gray whale dives into the ocean during a whale watching trip with Fast Raft Ocean Safaris in Monterey last month. Marine ecologist Ari Friedlaender, a researcher at UC Santa Cruz, and other Monterey Bay scientists are working with whale-watching companies. (Randy Vazquez – Bay Area News Group)

The jaws of two surface-feeding humpback whales snap shut around giant mouthfuls of anchovies in Monterey Bay near Moss Landing on Sept. 9, 2018. The whales will squeeze the water out the sides of their mouths through their comb-like baleen and swallow just the little fish.
(Courtesy of Kate Spencer, Fast Raft Ocean Safaris)
Credit/Source: (Courtesy of Kate Spencer, Fast Raft Ocean Safaris)

Caption: Ari Friedlaender from UCSC is tagging a humpback whale in Monterey Bay on October 19th, 2016. Jeremy Goldbogen, driving the boat, and Friedlaender are deploying a 3D movement camera tag to the whale to study the underwater behavior and foraging behavior of the whale in the bay. This is part of a long-term ecological study of whales in the bay. (Photo by James Fahlbusch/ National Marine Fisheries Service)
Credit/Source: (Photo by James Fahlbusch/ National Marine Fisheries Service)

Caption:
This humpback calf known as Kelper is especially playful and breaches repeatedly while its mother (CRC-15273) is busy feeding on anchovies with other adult whales and sea lions on Oct. 13, 2018 near Point Pinos in Monterey Bay. Kelper and all of the calves born in the winter of 2017-2018 in Central America are on their own this winter, figuring out how to feed themselves and exploring the coastline.
(Courtesy of Kate Spencer, Fast Raft Ocean Safaris)
Credit/Source: (Courtesy of Kate Spencer, Fast Raft Ocean Safaris)

Caption: Two adult humpback whales have a conversation with body language as they roll onto their right sides and loudly slap their left flippers against the water on Oct. 3, 2018 in Monterey Bay. These two might have a lot to talk about: One of them (CRC-10727) was first photographed as an adult in 1998, so it may be well over 30 years old. The other, Bottlenose (CRC-10846), is a female who is over 20 and had a calf in 2017. (Courtesy of Kate Spencer, Fast Raft Ocean Safaris)
Credit/Source: (Courtesy of Kate Spencer, Fast Raft Ocean Safaris)

Caption: Kate Spencer, of Fast Raft Ocean Safaris, is photographed in Monterey, Calif., on Wednesday, Jan. 2, 2019. Marine ecologist Ari Friedlaender, a researcher at UC Santa Cruz, and other Monterey Bay scientists are working with whale-watching companies. Both communities are helping each other. The companies will give Friedlaender much-needed data on where the whales are, while he will give the whale-watching companies updated scientific information for them to share with their customers. (Randy Vazquez/Bay Area News Group)
Humpback whales have been showing up in big numbers the past few months, with 42 just since January began. (Photo courtesy of Allison Santos/DolphinSafari.com)

A seagull is photographed trying to get food from some otters during a whale watching trip with Fast Raft Ocean Safaris in Monterey, Calif., on Wednesday, Jan. 2, 2019. Marine ecologist Ari Friedlaender, a researcher at UC Santa Cruz, and other Monterey Bay scientists are working with whale-watching companies. Both communities are helping each other. The companies will give Friedlaender much-needed data on where the whales are, while he will give the whale-watching companies updated scientific information for them to share with their customers. Shanique Marie, 25, of Vallejo, was killed in a shooting on Highway 4 near Railroad Avenue exit on May 11.

Marcus Gaines, 26, was arrested on suspicion of murder, according to Pittsburg police. Gaines and three other men are  suspected of shooting at a man and a woman, who later died, on May 11 on Highway 4 near the Railroad Avenue overpass.

Damario Pitteard, 23, is suspected of shooting at a man and a woman, who later died, on May 11 on Highway 4 near the Railroad Avenue overpass, according to Pittsburg police. He has an outstanding murder warrant out for his arrest.

Corey McCroey, 25, is suspected of shooting at a man and a woman, who later died, on May 11 on Highway 4 near the Railroad Avenue overpass, according to Pittsburg police. He has an outstanding murder warrant out for his arrest.

Kevin Carter, 22, was arrested on suspicion of murder, according to Pittsburg police. Carter and three other men are  suspected of shooting at a man and a woman, who later died, on May 11 on Highway 4 near the Railroad Avenue overpass

Caption:
Alexandra Minor/U.S. Air Force
						In this Air Force photo obtained Nov. 13, 2018, soldiers with the 889th Engineering Support Company lay concertina wire along the Gateway International Bridge in Brownsville, Texas, while the 89th Military Police Brigade, provide security. Thousands more troops will head to the U.S.-Mexico border, acting Defense Secretary Patrick Shanahan said January 29, 2019, as part of a controversial mission to enhance security along the frontier. Currently, about 2,350 active-duty troops are working along the border, where they are helping border patrol agents by providing logistical support and installing concertina-wire fencing.

Caption:
Alfredo Estrella/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images
						In this photo taken on Feb. 22, 2014, Mexican drug trafficker Joaquin Guzman Loera, aka “El Chapo” Guzman, is escorted by marines as he is presented to the press in Mexico City. A witness in the trial of Guzman told the U.S. government the Mexican drug kingpin drugged and raped girls as young as 13, according to court documents unsealed February 2, 2019. Longtime associate Alex Cifuentes told authorities a woman would send Guzman photos of young girls to choose from, with a fee of $5,000 per girl. Cifuentes used this service himself three or four times, having sex with girls as young as 15 years old, the government said in the documents, adding he “witnessed the defendant do the same on multiple occasions, with girls as young as 13 years old.”
Credit/Source: Alfredo Estrella/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images

Caption: Rendering of Bascom Avenue in the South Bay. (Santa Clara ValleyTransportation Authority)

CalTrans defines a Complete Street as a “transportation facility
that is planned, designed, operated, and maintained to provide safe mobility for all users, including bicyclists, pedestrians, transit riders, truckers, and motorists appropriate to the function and context of the facility.”

This stretch of Main Street in Bridgeport, California underwent a “road diet” or “rightsizing,” which reduced the total number of driving lanes from four to three while bike lanes were added. (CalTrans)
A new buffered bike lane adds space between the driving lane and cyclists on SR 35 Sloat Blvd in San Francisco. (CalTrans)
So-called “high visibility crosswalks” are a feature of Complete Streets, as seen in this photograph of the intersection at El Camino Real (SR-82) and Mission Street in Daly City. (CalTrans

Crossing islands like this one on Samoa Boulevard (SR-255) in Arcata allow pedestrians to cross fewer lanes and
directions of traffic at a time, according to CalTrans. 
(CalTrans)
Shoulders on Complete Streets are colorized to provide additional visibility for bicyclists. (CalTrans)
Green painted pavement on bikeways is used to reportedly increase cyclist visibility at right turn pockets, driveways freeway on-ramps and off-ramps and intersections (CalTrans)

Brian Simmons, a long time Oakland resident, uses the new bike lanes or "cycle tracks" along Telegraph Avenue in the KONO district of Oakland, Calif., on Tuesday, May 10, 2016.  (Laura A. Oda/Bay Area News Group)

Date: PUBLISHED: February 3, 2019 at 8:00 am | UPDATED: February 4, 2019 at 2:35 am
Caption: Employee Linda Cole is dwarfed by the mammoth replica on display at the Fossil Discovery Center of Madera County in Chowchilla. The facility is located at the Fairmead landfill, the site of one of the largest middle-Pleistocene fossil excavations in North America. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

The full scale model of a Columbian mammoth dominates the main room of the Fossil Discovery Center of Madera County. The center is across the street from the Fairmead Landfill, the site of 15,000 fossil excavations. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)
Among the fossils discovered at the landfill on the 1990s are saber-tooth cats, mammoths, camels and horses. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

Upon paying admission at the center, guests are escorted to a theater for a short film explaining the Fairmead dig discoveries and what the San Joaquin Valley may have looked like 700,000 years ago. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

The Mammoth Orange, an Abandoned Highway 99 landmark, has been rescued by the Fossil Discovery Center of Madera County, where it sits outdoors. The center plans to restore the icon and pair it with their Columbian Mammoth display to attract visitors to their middle-Pleistocene fossil collection. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

Caption: This picture taken Feb. 2, 2019, shows artifact fragments on display outside newly-discovered burial chambers dating to the Ptolemaic era (305-30 BC) at the necropolis of Tuna el-Gebel in Egypt's southern Minya province, about 340 kilometers south of Cairo. Egypt's Antiquities Minister said that a joint mission from the ministry and Minya University's Archaeological Studies Research Centre found the collection of Ptolemaic burial chambers engraved in rock and filled with a large number of mummies of different sizes and genders.
Credit/Source: Mohamed El-Shahed/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images

Caption: This picture taken on Feb. 2, 2019, shows newly-discovered mummies wrapped in linen found in burial chambers dating to the Ptolemaic era (305-30 BC) at the necropolis of Tuna el-Gebel in Egypt's southern Minya province, about 340 kilometers south of the capital Cairo. Officials said that the newly discovered tombs may be a familial grave for a family from the elite middle class.
Credit/Source: Mohamed El-Shahed/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images

Caption: This picture taken on Feb. 2, 2019, shows the partially-uncovered skull of a newly-discovered mummy wrapped in linen found in a burial chamber dating to the Ptolemaic era (305-30 BC) at the necropolis of Tuna el-Gebel in Egypt's southern Minya province.
Credit/Source: Mohamed El-Shahed/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images

Credit/Source: Mohamed El-Shahed/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images

Caption: An archaeologist brushes a newly-discovered mummy laid inside a sarcophagus, part of a collection found in burial chambers dating to the Ptolemaic era (305-30 BC) at the necropolis of Tuna el-Gebel in Egypt's southern Minya province. Egypt's Antiquities Minister said that a joint mission from the ministry and Minya University's Archaeological Studies Research Centre found the collection of Ptolemaic burial chambers engraved in rock and filled with a large number of mummies of different sizes and genders. Date: PUBLISHED: February 2, 2019 at 10:20 am | UPDATED: February 3, 2019 at 12:17 am
Caption: The upheaval of more than 1 million foreign workers in Saudi Arabia since 2017 has added to a sense of uncertainty in the country.
In Jiddah, above, as in other Saudi cities, buildings are emptying and stores staffed by foreigners are struggling or shuttered.
Abdul Mageed, 29, is a produce worker in a Pakistani neighborhood of Jiddah. He moved to Saudi Arabia four years ago but plans to leave in a year because of high fees imposed by the Saudi government.
Christian Lacap, 31, is from the Philippines and has worked in Saudi Arabia for the past seven years. He is among the exodus of single men leaving.
Lacap, who works in a restaurant, did not have a job lined up in the Philippines and hopes to work in another country -- perhaps South Korea or Canada.
A man makes his way to a mosque in a Pakistani neighborhood in Jiddah.

Caption: PARADISE CA – JAN. 23: Bill Krulder, who works at the Save Mart supermarket in Paradise, Calif., recalls Wednesday, Jan. 23, 2019, how he and hundreds of neighbors were forced to shelter in the store’s parking lot after getting trapped by the Camp Fire last year. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

MAGALIA, CA - JAN. 23: Pastor Doug Crowder reflects back on the deadly Camp Fire inside a classroom at the Magalia Pines Baptist Church in Magalia, Calif., Sunday, Jan. 23, 2019."We had a plan, and it went up in flames," said Crowder, whose church became a refuge for 30 people who survived the deadliest wildfire in California history. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

PARADISE, CA - JAN. 24: Crosses commemorate the 86 victims of the Camp Fire, the deadliest wildfire in state history, on a hilltop in Paradise, Calif., Tuesday, Jan. 22, 2019. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

CAMP FIRE 2018: This Thursday, Nov. 15, 2018, file aerial photo shows the remains of residences leveled by the wildfire in Paradise, Calif. California's attorney general has told a federal judge it's possible Pacific Gas & Electric Co. could face charges up to murder if investigators find reckless operation of power equipment caused any deadly wildfires in the past two years. The Sacramento Bee reports the brief is purely advisory and any criminal charges would most likely be filed by county district attorneys. (AP Photo/Noah Berger, File)
CAMP FIRE 2018: Sacramento Metropolitan firefighters battle the Camp Fire in Magalia, Calif., Friday, November 9, 2018. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

PARADISE, CALIFORNIA - NOVEMBER 21: Firefighters search for human remains in the ashes of the Black Bear Diner in Paradise, Calif., Wednesday, Nov. 21, 2018, nearly two weeks after the Camp Fire started. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

MAGALIA, CA - JAN. 23: Pastor Doug Crowder (left) walks with a truck drive delivering supplies to Magalia Pines Baptist Church in Magalia, Calif., Wednesday, Jan. 23, 2019. The church was a refuge for 30 people sheltering from the Camp Fire late last year, and it is now a resource for the community as it recovers. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

Chris and Nancy Brown embrace while searching through the remains of their home, leveled by the Camp Fire, in Paradise, Calif., on Monday, Nov. 12, 2018. As the fire approached, Nancy Brown escaped from the home with her 2-year-old and three dogs. (AP Photo/Noah Berger)
CAMP FIRE 2018: Flames burn inside a van as the Camp Fire tears through Paradise, Calif., on Thursday, Nov. 8, 2018. (AP Photo/Noah Berger, File)

PARADISE, CA - JAN. 23: Christina Taft visits the commemorative cross honoring her mother, Victoria Taft, one of 86 Camp Fire victim crosses set up on a hillside in Paradise, Calif., Wednesday, Jan. 23, 2019. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

Caption: In this photo taken by Jade Davis, Guanrong Rivera and Jose Luis Rivera were seen loading bags of stolen succulents into their vehicle. The photo was used as evidence in their conviction Thursday Jan. 31 in Monterey County Superior Court. (Photo courtesy of Jade Davis.)

Volunteers gathered on Monday, April 16, 2018, to replant more than 2,000 Dudleya succulents which had been seized from poachers who dug the plants up from their moorings on California’s rocky coastlines in Mendocino and Humboldt counties. (Courtesy CDFW)

Two unidentified men are photographed by warden Patrick Freeling after he arrested them in connection with the alleged poaching of Dudleya succulent plants, harvested by the men from the Humboldt County coast. The plants are typically boxed up and shipped to countries like Korea, where they are sold for $40 to $50 a plant. (Courtesy Patrick Freeling/CDFW)

Date: PUBLISHED: February 2, 2019 at 6:00 am | UPDATED: February 3, 2019 at 2:03 pm
Caption: CAMP FIRE 2018: In this Nov. 9, 2018 file photo, Pacific Gas & Electric crews work to restore power lines in Paradise, Calif. CaliforniaÕs largest utility company is getting battered in midday trading on a report that itÕs considering bankruptcy protection in the face of potentially crippling liability damages from a spate of recent wildfires. No cause has been determined for the source of CaliforniaÕs ÒCamp Fire,Ó but PG&E reported an outage around the time and place the fire was ignited. Another transmission line also malfunctioned a short time later, possibly sparking a second fire. (AP Photo/Rich Pedroncelli, File)

PARADISE, CALIFORNIA – NOVEMBER 21: Pacific Gas and Electric (PG&E) crews repair power lines that were destroyed by the Camp Fire on November 21, 2018 in Paradise, California. Fueled by high winds and low humidity the Camp Fire ripped through the town of Paradise charring over 150,000 acres, killed at least 81 people and has destroyed over 18,000 homes and businesses. The fire is currently at 80 percent containment and hundreds of people still remain missing. (Photo by Justin Sullivan/Getty Images)

CAMP FIRE 2018: Protesters hold signs as they march to the Pacific Gas and Electric (PG&E) headquarters on December 11, 2018 in San Francisco, California. More than two dozens protesters staged a demonstration inside the lobby of the PG&E headquarters to demand that the energy company be held accountable for the Camp Fire that killed 85 people and destroyed over 18,000 structures in and around Paradise, California last month. (Photo by Justin Sullivan/Getty Images)
SOLANO COUNTY, CA – JAN. 29: PG&E transmission towers rise above a cluster of windmills in Solano County south of Rio Vista, Tuesday, Jan. 29, 2019. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)

Caption: My dog and cat, Gracie Mae and Max, snuggling on a cold winter night. (Courtesy of Tena Hogan)
Maddie and Oscar have been best friends ever since they met! They love to wrestle and run each time they see one another.  I am so happy they have each other. (Courtesy of Sheri Madsen)

My lovely Hannah with her rescue "old girl," Bella.  We think she is an Australian cattle dog and was back at same adoption fair after being returned twice when Hannah saw her. She was not going to be put up again after that day because of her age and several health issues.  My daughter fell in love with her big brown eyes and now I call them Frick and Frack because they cannot be separated. (Courtesy of Vicki Wyant)

My two girls -- Stella, the gray one,  rescued from the local shelter, and Peanut, rescued from my front porch in the rain. When Peanut can't find Stella she cries very loudly. They love this cat tree and spend all their sleeping time here, usually fighting over the top bunk. (Courtesy of Debbie Hart)

This is my Samoyeds, Pony and Larry. Larry, on the right, is Pony's father. They were always very close and loved each other very much. They romped in the yard together. They played with toys together, with Pony often trying to distract Larry so she could get his toy. But Larry knew her little game and easily gave up his toys to his daughter. Oftentimes, they would just lie next to each other, share kisses and enjoy each other's company. As you know how it always goes, sadly, Pony and I lost Larry in August 2017 when he was 14-1/2. Pony clearly grieved her father's passing, as did I. Thank goodness we have each other. Pony is truly my Valentine every day. (Courtesy of Gail Campbell)
Mitzi, a petite spaniel mix, and Peanut, Chihuahua-dachshund mix, rescues who love each other. (Courtesy of Roddie and Dave Stelle)
Counterclockwise from front, Luci, Desi and Danno (technically, Lucinda, Pollux and Bookemdanno), two Balinese and a Thai. (Courtesy of Pat and Art Still)
Buster loves to get groomed by Walker. They are both 10-year-old rescues. (Courtesy of Ann Fine)
Vinnie and Kona. (Courtesy of Paula Russell)
Gidget, our new rescue, getting to know her big sister, Poppy. (Courtesy of Michelle Luevano)

Caption:
Saul Loeb/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images
						A man types on a computer keyboard in this photo illustration taken in Washington, DC, November 21, 2016.
Almost half of US internet users say they have been a victim of online harassment or abuse ranging from name-calling to stalking to physical threats, a survey showed November 21, 2016. Women, the under-30s, and people identifying as lesbian, gay, or bisexual were all more likely to experience such harassment — and were also more likely to self-censor what they post online as a result, researchers found.More than a third (36 percent) had suffered “direct harassment,” including being called offensive names, threatened physically or stalked.
 / AFP PHOTO / SAUL LOEB        (Photo credit should read SAUL LOEB/AFP/Getty Images)

Getty Images
						Having a pet can bring joy and enrich lives no matter your age, but for older people who don’t get out much, pets can offer special companionship.

Dogs are known as a human's best friend. But which breeds are sought-after among Americans? Here is a look at the most popular types of dogs in the U.S., according to the American Kennel Club. (Dan Rosenstrauch/Bay Area News Group)

No. 1 Labrador retrievers: Nestlé, a 5 1/2 month-old labrador retriever, with a local chapter of the Guide Dogs for the Blind, in Terminal A during a training session at San Jose International Airport in San Jose, Calif. on Monday, Sept. 23, 2013.  (Nhat V. Meyer/Bay Area News Group)

No. 1 Labrador retrievers: Karen Zelis, left, the facilitator of the Contra Costa County District Attorney's courthouse dog program, and Mary Pickett, handler to the newly hired courthouse dog, sit inside  Department 3 with JoJo at the A.F. Bray Courthouse in Martinez, Calif., on Friday, Oct. 30, 2015. JoJo, a calm and loving female Labrador Rretriever and the first courthouse dog in Contra Costa County, is a supportive presence to traumatized children and adults as they go through the criminal justice process. (Dan Rosenstrauch/Bay Area News Group)

No. 2. German Shepherd: Two German Shepherd puppies were rescued by San Leandro police after officers arrested a man suspected of taking the dogs from a Livermore home last week. (San Leandro Police Department)

No. 2 German Shepherd: Gypsy is a spayed female, black and tan German Shepherd Dog available for
adoption.
Courtesy Contra Costa Animal Services

No. 3 golden retriever: 50-day-old Golden Retriever puppies are seen at the Chilean police canine training school in Santiago, on October 09, 2018. (Martin Bernetti/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images)

No. 3 golden retriever: Chilean policeman Eduardo Parra, in charge of the police dogs maternity area, holds 50-day-old Golden Retriever puppies after their training session at the Chilean police canine training school in Santiago, on October 09, 2018. (Photo by Martin Bernetti/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images)
Credit/Source: (Photo by Martin Bernetti/Agence France-Presse via Getty Images)

Date: PUBLISHED: January 28, 2019 at 9:19 am | UPDATED: January 29, 2019 at 2:16 pm
Caption:
The Duchess of Sussex attended the opening of ‘Oceania’ at the Royal Academy of Arts 
 Oceania’ is the first ever major survey of Oceanic art to be held in the United Kingdom. The exhibition will celebrate the art of Melanesia, Micronesia and Polynesia, encompassing the vast Pacific region including New Guinea, Easter Island, Hawaii and New Zealand. ‘Oceania’ will bring together around 200 works from public collections worldwide, spanning over 500 years. The exhibition also marks the 250th anniversary of the Royal Academy, which was founded in 1768 – the same year Captain James Cook set out on his first Endeavour expedition.
 Picture: Arthur Edwards

Caption: YOSEMITE, CA - JAN. 11:  Empty gates and snow greet visitors to Yosemite National Park on Highway 41, Friday, Jan. 11, 2019, as the park remains open to visitors though services are limited due to the partial government shutdown. (Karl Mondon/Bay Area News Group)
